title: For Sale:  M1917 Enfield .30-06 EXCELLENT CONDITION
postcontent: Offered is my M1917 rifle in Excellent Condition, nicest M1917 I have ever seen. This rifle is 100% original with the original cartouche marks on the stock. It is fully functional and everything is intact and works as it should. I bought this rifle in 1987 when the Firearms Protection Act of 1986 allowed the importation of surplus military rifles into our country again. This rifle is from the first batch of imports from that era and these early imports were hand picked and were the best of the bunch. I removed the cosmoline this rifle came packed in, wiped it down, and fired 20 rds of non corrosive ammo thru it for a functions check, everything worked as it should and it shot a very tight respectable group. I then cleaned the bore, applied a light coat of oil to everything, then put it into my climatically controlled vault where it has sat largely untouched since. This rifle is complete, fully intact, fully function, shoots to point of aim and has not been modified, restored, or altered in anyway from its original configuration. The condition of this rifle is far above that of most M1917s I have seen; the blueing is very nice, there is no rust, the stock is in very good original condition, and 27 years ago I put a US milspec leather sling on it that still looks like the day it was made. The bore has no pitting or rust that I can see with a bore light and the rifling is excellent; the lands and grooves and sharp and crisp. You will not be disappointed with this rifle. I am retiring and have way too many guns than I can take with me when I move so I am selling the last and best of my military rifle collection. I will meet buyer between Charlotte Hall and Upper Marlboro for a FTF cash and carry deal during daylight hours in a public setting, buyer must be MD resident or active duty military living in MD. This sale has no tax, no shipping or transfer fees, no paper work, no govt registration, and it is available now, and this transaction is 100% legal in the state of Maryland. Buyer must be a MD resident who is not prohibited by law from owning firearms or active duty military living in MD. Will meet buyer in a public place for a FTF cash and carry deal during day light hours. title: For Sale:  Marlin Golden 39A .22 Lever Action
location: Santa Fe, NM, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
I never shoot this rifle anymore, so I may as well sell it. I am seeing them on the Gunbroker.com go for a LOT more than this I think. Check them out and see. These have always been expensive rifles, and they are even more-so now that Remington has bought out Marlin. This is a real Marlin though and is a quality rifle. 

I would rather that it go to a local New Mexican here than an auction, so I will list it for a few days. If nobody wants it, I'll take it to the auction online. Pictures show the rifle without the original white line spacers installed. Fortunately the previous owner was conscientious enough to include them when I bought the rifle. I never reinstalled them just because I liked the way it looks better without them. They will come with the rifle, or I can just install them before you pick it up. 

Condition is almost perfect except for one thing. The rear swivel has been relocated back about 1 1/2 inches. The original hole has been nicely plugged with a polished wooden peg. It is only visible from the bottom, and fits quite well. Anyone who wants to change it should be able to put a wood screw in it and then pull it out. I was told it is a friction fit on that plug. The original seller/owner is a friend of mine and I have absolutely no reason to doubt him since he has always been a straight shooter to me.

 Other than that , I would rate the rifle at about 99%. Bore is perfect, no scratches on the metal, etc. I never actually bench rested it, but I do recall shooting Coke cans regularly at 100 yards with no problem. It is right in there with my old Winchester Model 62A in that department. Empty shotgun shells offhand at 25 yards are so little challenge that I moved them out to 50. These rifles hang well, and if you are considering it, you probably already know that. I have never taken it hunting and neither did the previous owner, so it has no field dings or briar scratches, etc. It is a nice rifle, and other than the plug repair it looks brand new.

Contact me through Armslist with your phone number and we can arrange to meet. I no longer put my number in these ads because of all the Nigerian scammers out there. They will email me but I won't even reply. You shouldn't either, since they are just looking for your email address or phone number.

At any rate, thanks for reading my ad. If I didn't already have a thousand dollar .22 plinker, I would keep this one. I will miss it for sure.

Doby Pilgrim
Santa Fe, NM
